# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cuda-programming
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA is both a software layer that manages data, giving direct access to the GPU and CPU as necessary, and a library of APIs that enable parallel computation for various needs.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] In addition to drivers and runtime kernels, the CUDA platform includes compilers, libraries and developer tools to help programmers accelerate their applications.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA is written in the C programming language but is designed to work with a wide array of other programming languages including C++, Fortran, Python and Julia.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] This accessibility makes it easier for specialists in parallel programming to use GPU resources, in contrast to prior APIs like Direct3D and OpenGL, which require advanced skills in graphics programming.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA-powered GPUs also support programming frameworks such as OpenMP, OpenACC and OpenCL.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The graphics processing unit (GPU), as a specialized computer processor, addresses the demands of real-time high-resolution 3D graphics compute-intensive tasks.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] By 2012, GPUs had evolved into highly parallel multi-core systems allowing efficient manipulation of large blocks of data.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The origins of CUDA trace to the early 2000s, when Ian Buck, a computer science Ph.D. student at Stanford University, began experimenting with using GPUs for purposes beyond rendering graphics.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Buck had first become interested in GPUs during his undergraduate studies at Princeton University, initially through video gaming.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] After graduation, he interned at Nvidia, gaining deeper exposure to GPU architecture.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] At Stanford, he built an 8K gaming rig using 32 GeForce graphics cards, originally to push the limits of graphics performance in games like Quake and Doom.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] However, his interests shifted toward exploring the potential of GPUs for general-purpose parallel computing.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] To that end, Buck developed Brook, a programming language designed to enable general-purpose computing on GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] His work attracted support from both Nvidia and the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] In 2004, Nvidia hired Buck and paired him with John Nickolls, the company's director of architecture for GPU computing.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Together, they began transforming Brook into what would become CUDA.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA was officially released by Nvidia in 2007.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Under the leadership of Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang, CUDA became central to the company's strategy of positioning GPUs as versatile hardware for scientific applications.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] By 2015, CUDA's development increasingly focused on accelerating machine learning and artificial neural network workloads.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The following table offers a non-exact description for the ontology of the CUDA framework.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The CUDA platform is accessible to software developers through CUDA-accelerated libraries, compiler directives such as OpenACC, and extensions to industry-standard programming languages including C, C++, Fortran and Python.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] C/C++ programmers can use 'CUDA C/C++', compiled to PTX with nvcc (Nvidia's LLVM-based C/C++ compiler) or by clang itself.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Fortran programmers can use 'CUDA Fortran', compiled with the PGI CUDA Fortran compiler from The Portland Group.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Python programmers can use the cuPyNumeric library to accelerate applications on Nvidia GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] In addition to libraries, compiler directives, CUDA C/C++ and CUDA Fortran, the CUDA platform supports other computational interfaces, including the Khronos Group's OpenCL, Microsoft's DirectCompute, OpenGL Compute Shader and C++ AMP.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Third party wrappers are also available for Python, Perl, Fortran, Java, Ruby, Lua, Common Lisp, Haskell, R, MATLAB, IDL, Julia, and native support in Mathematica.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] In the computer game industry, GPUs are used for graphics rendering, and for game physics calculations (physical effects such as debris, smoke, fire, fluids); examples include PhysX and Bullet.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA has also been used to accelerate non-graphical applications in computational biology, cryptography and other fields by an order of magnitude or more.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA provides both a low level API (CUDA **Driver** API, non single-source) and a higher level API (CUDA **Runtime** API, single-source).
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The initial CUDA SDK was made public on 15 February 2007, for Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Mac OS X support was later added in version 2.0, which supersedes the beta released February 14, 2008.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA works with all Nvidia GPUs from the G8x series onwards, including GeForce, Quadro and the Tesla line.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA is compatible with most standard operating systems.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Below is an example given in Python that computes the product of two arrays on the GPU.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The unofficial Python language bindings can be obtained from *PyCUDA*.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Additional Python bindings to simplify matrix multiplication operations can be found in the program *pycublas*.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Note on notation: compute capability X.Y is also written as SMXY or sm_XY (e.g.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] 10.3 as SM103 or sm_103) in professional Nvidia software and the code Nvidia has contributed to LLVM.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Note: CUDA SDK 10.2 is the last official release for macOS, as support will not be available for macOS in newer releases.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Note: A GPU with a higher compute capacity is able to execute PTX code meant for a GPU of a lower range of compute capacities.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] However, it is possible to compile CUDA code into a form that only works on one family (same "X") of GPUs; if existing code is compiled this way, recompilation will be needed for it to work on a newer GPU.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Note: Any missing lines or empty entries do reflect some lack of information on that exact item.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] For more information read the Nvidia CUDA C++ Programming Guide.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] CUDA competes with other GPU computing stacks: Intel OneAPI and AMD ROCm.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Whereas Nvidia's CUDA is closed-source, Intel's OneAPI and AMD's ROCm are open source.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] Originally made by Intel, other hardware adopters include Fujitsu and Huawei.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The goal is to offer open alternatives to Nvidia's CUDA.
[src:cuda-programming/cuda] The main companies behind it are Intel, Google, ARM, Qualcomm, Samsung, Imagination, and VMware.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:cuda-programming/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:cuda-programming/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Originally focused on GPUs for video games, Nvidia broadened their use into other markets, including artificial intelligence (AI), professional visualization, and supercomputing.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The company's product lines include GeForce GPUs for gaming and creative workloads, and professional GPUs for edge computing, scientific research, and industrial applications.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As of the first quarter of 2025, Nvidia held a 92% share of the discrete desktop and laptop GPU market.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In the early-to-mid 2000s, the company invested over a billion dollars to develop CUDA, a software platform and API (Application Programming Interfaces) that enabled GPUs to run massively parallel programs for a broad range of compute-intensive applications.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As a result, as of 2025, Nvidia controlled more than 80% of the market for GPUs used in training and deploying AI models, and provided chips for over 75% of the world's TOP500 supercomputers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The company has also expanded into gaming hardware and services, with products such as the Shield Portable, Shield Tablet, and Shield TV, and operates the GeForce Now cloud gaming service.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Furthermore, it has developed the Tegra line of mobile processors for smartphones, tablets, and automotive infotainment systems.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 2023, Nvidia became the seventh U.S. company to reach a US$1 trillion valuation.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 2025, amid increased demand for AI data center hardware in the midst of the AI boom, Nvidia became the first company in the world to surpass US$4 trillion and US$5 trillion in market capitalization.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Because of its market capitalization and role in major technology indexes, Nvidia has been selected as one of Bloomberg's "Magnificent Seven", the seven biggest companies on the stock market in these regards.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In late 1992, the three men agreed to start the company in a meeting at a Denny's roadside diner on Berryessa Road in East San Jose.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] At the time, Malachowsky and Priem were frustrated with Sun's management and were looking to leave, but Huang was on "firmer ground", in that he was already running his own division at LSI.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The three co-founders discussed a vision of the future which was so compelling that Huang decided to leave LSI and become the chief executive officer of their new startup.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The three co-founders envisioned graphics-based processing as the best trajectory for tackling challenges that had eluded general-purpose computing methods.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As Huang later explained: "We also observed that video games were simultaneously one of the most computationally challenging problems and would have incredibly high sales volume.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Those two conditions don't happen very often.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The first problem was who would quit first.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Huang's wife, Lori, did not want him to resign from LSI unless Malachowsky resigned from Sun at the same time, and Malachowsky's wife, Melody, felt the same way about Huang.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Priem broke that deadlock by resigning first from Sun, effective December 31, 1992.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] According to Priem, this put pressure on Huang and Malachowsky to not leave him to "flail alone", so they gave notice too.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Huang left LSI and "officially joined Priem on February 17", which was also Huang's 30th birthday, while Malachowsky left Sun in early March.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In early 1993, the three founders began working together on their new startup in Priem's townhouse in Fremont, California.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] With $40,000 in the bank (equivalent to $89,000 in 2025), the company was born.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The company subsequently received $20 million of venture capital funding from Sequoia Capital, Sutter Hill Ventures, and others.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] During the late 1990s, Nvidia was one of 70 startup companies pursuing the idea that graphics acceleration for video games was the path to the future.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Only two survived: Nvidia and ATI Technologies, the latter of which merged into AMD.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Priem's first idea was "Primal Graphics", a syllabic abbreviation of two of the founders' last names, but that left out Huang.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] They soon discovered it was impossible to create a workable name with syllables from all three founders' names, after considering "Huaprimal", "Prihuamal", "Malluapri", etc.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The next idea came from Priem's idea for the name of Nvidia's first product.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Priem originally wanted to call it the "GXNV", as in the "next version" of the GX graphics chips which he had worked on at Sun.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Then Huang told Priem to "drop the GX", resulting in the name "NV".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Priem made a list of words with the letters "NV" in them.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] At one point, Malachowsky and Priem wanted to call the company NVision, but that name was already taken by a manufacturer of toilet paper.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Both Priem and Huang have taken credit for coming up with the name Nvidia, from "invidia", the Latin word for "envy".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] After the company outgrew Priem's townhouse, its original headquarters office was in Sunnyvale, California.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's first graphics accelerator, the NV1, was designed to process quadrilateral primitives (forward texture mapping), a feature that set it apart from competitors, who preferred triangle primitives.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] However, when Microsoft introduced the DirectX platform, it chose not to support any other graphics software and announced that its Direct3D API would exclusively support triangles.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As a result, the NV1 failed to gain traction in the market.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia had also entered into a partnership with Sega to supply the graphics chip for the Dreamcast console and worked on the project for about a year.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] However, Nvidia's technology was already lagging behind competitors.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This placed the company in a difficult position: continue working on a chip that was likely doomed to fail or abandon the project, risking financial collapse.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In a pivotal moment, Sega's president, Shoichiro Irimajiri, visited Huang in person to inform him that Sega had decided to choose another vendor for the Dreamcast.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] However, Irimajiri believed in Nvidia's potential and persuaded Sega's management to invest $5 million into the company.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Huang later reflected that this funding was all that kept Nvidia afloat, and that Irimajiri's "understanding and generosity gave us six months to live".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 1996, Huang laid off more than half of Nvidia's employees-reducing headcount from 100 to 40-and focused the company's remaining resources on developing a graphics accelerator product optimized for processing triangle primitives: the RIVA 128.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] By the time the RIVA 128 was released in August 1997, Nvidia had only enough money left for one month's payroll.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The sense of impending failure became so pervasive that it gave rise to Nvidia's unofficial company motto: "Our company is thirty days from going out of business." Huang began internal presentations to Nvidia staff with those words for many years.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia sold about a million RIVA 128 units within four months, and used the revenue to fund development of its next generation of products.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 1998, the release of the RIVA TNT helped solidify Nvidia's reputation as a leader in graphics technology.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Investing in Nvidia after it had already failed to deliver on its contract turned out to be Irimajiri's best decision as Sega's president.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] After Irimajiri left Sega in 2000, Sega sold its Nvidia stock for $15 million.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In late 1999, Nvidia released the GeForce 256 (NV10), its first product expressly marketed as a GPU, which was most notable for introducing onboard transformation and lighting (T&L) to consumer-level 3D hardware.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Running at 120 MHz and featuring four-pixel pipelines, it implemented advanced video acceleration, motion compensation, and hardware sub-picture alpha blending.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The GeForce outperformed existing products by a wide margin.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Because its products were performing well, Nvidia won the contract to develop the graphics hardware for Microsoft's Xbox game console, which included a $200 million advance.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] However, the project took many of its best engineers away from other projects.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In the short term this did not matter, and the GeForce 2 GTS shipped in the summer of 2000.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In December 2000, Nvidia reached an agreement to acquire the intellectual assets of its one-time rival 3dfx, a pioneer in consumer 3D graphics technology leading the field from the mid-1990s until 2000.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The acquisition process was finalized in April 2002.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 2001, Standard & Poor's selected Nvidia to replace the departing Enron in the S&P 500 stock index, meaning that index funds would need to hold Nvidia shares going forward.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In July 2002, Nvidia acquired Exluna for an undisclosed sum.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Exluna made software-rendering tools and its personnel were merged into Nvidia's Cg project.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In August 2003, Nvidia acquired MediaQ for approximately US$70 million.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On April 22, 2004, Nvidia acquired iReady, also a provider of high-performance TCP offload engines and iSCSI controllers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In December 2004, it was announced that Nvidia would assist Sony with the design of the graphics processor (RSX) for the PlayStation 3 game console.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On December 14, 2005, Nvidia acquired ULI Electronics, which at the time supplied third-party southbridge parts for chipsets to ATI, Nvidia's competitor.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In March 2006, Nvidia acquired Hybrid Graphics.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In December 2006, Nvidia, along with its main rival in the graphics industry AMD (which had acquired ATI), received subpoenas from the United States Department of Justice regarding possible antitrust violations in the graphics card industry.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In July 2008, Nvidia took a write-down of approximately $200 million on its first-quarter revenue, after reporting that certain mobile chipsets and GPUs produced by the company had "abnormal failure rates" due to manufacturing defects.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia, however, did not reveal the affected products.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In September 2008, Nvidia became the subject of a class action lawsuit over the defects, claiming that the faulty GPUs had been incorporated into certain laptop models manufactured by Apple Inc., Dell, and HP.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In September 2010, Nvidia reached a settlement, in which it would reimburse owners of the affected laptops for repairs or, in some cases, replacement.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On January 10, 2011, Nvidia signed a six-year, $1.5 billion cross-licensing agreement with Intel, ending all litigation between the two companies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In November 2011, after initially unveiling it at Mobile World Congress, Nvidia released its ARM-based system on a chip for mobile devices, Tegra 3.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia claimed that the chip featured the first-ever quad-core mobile CPU.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2011, it was announced that Nvidia had agreed to acquire Icera, a baseband chip making company in the UK, for $367 million.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In January 2013, Nvidia unveiled the Tegra 4, as well as the Nvidia Shield, an Android-based handheld game console powered by the new system on a chip.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On July 29, 2013, Nvidia announced that it acquired PGI from STMicroelectronics.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In February 2013, Nvidia announced its plans to build a new headquarters in the form of two giant triangle-shaped buildings on the other side of San Tomas Expressway (to the west of its existing headquarters complex).
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The company selected triangles as its design theme.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As Huang explained in a blog post, the triangle is "the fundamental building block of computer graphics".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 2014, Nvidia ported the Valve games *Portal* and *Half Life 2* to its Nvidia Shield Tablet as Lightspeed Studio.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Since 2014, Nvidia has diversified its business focusing on three markets: gaming, automotive electronics, and mobile devices.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] That same year, Nvidia also prevailed in litigation brought by the trustee of 3dfx's bankruptcy estate to challenge its 2000 acquisition of 3dfx's intellectual assets.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On May 6, 2016, Nvidia unveiled the first GPUs of the GeForce 10 series, the GTX 1080 and 1070, based on the company's new Pascal microarchitecture.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia claimed that both models outperformed its Maxwell-based Titan X model; the models incorporate GDDR5X and GDDR5 memory respectively, and use a 16 nm manufacturing process.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The architecture also supports a new hardware feature known as simultaneous multi-projection (SMP), which is designed to improve the quality of multi-monitor and virtual reality (VR) rendering.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Laptops that include these GPUs and are sufficiently thin – as of late 2017, under 0.8 inches (20 mm) – have been designated as meeting Nvidia's "Max-Q" design standard.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In July 2016, Nvidia agreed to a settlement for a false advertising lawsuit regarding its GTX 970 model, as the models were unable to use all of their advertised 4 GB of VRAM due to limitations brought by the design of its hardware.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2017, Nvidia announced a partnership with Toyota which would use Nvidia's Drive PX-series artificial intelligence platform for its autonomous vehicles.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In July 2017, Nvidia and Chinese search giant Baidu announced a far-reaching AI partnership that includes cloud computing, autonomous driving, consumer devices, and Baidu's open-source AI framework PaddlePaddle.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Baidu unveiled that Nvidia's Drive PX 2 AI will be the foundation of its autonomous-vehicle platform.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia released the Titan V on December 7, 2017.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia released the Nvidia Quadro GV100 on March 27, 2018.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia released the RTX 2080 GPUs on September 27, 2018.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 2018, Google announced that Nvidia's Tesla P4 graphic cards would be integrated into Google Cloud service's artificial intelligence.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2018, on the Nvidia user forum, a thread was started asking the company to update users when it would release web drivers for its cards installed on legacy Mac Pro machines up to mid-2012 5,1 running the macOS Mojave operating system 10.14.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Web drivers are required to enable graphics acceleration and multiple display monitor capabilities of the GPU.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On its Mojave update info website, Apple stated that macOS Mojave would run on legacy machines with 'Metal compatible' graphics cards and listed Metal compatible GPUs, including some manufactured by Nvidia.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] However, this list did not include Metal compatible cards that currently work in macOS High Sierra using Nvidia-developed web drivers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In September, Nvidia responded, "Apple fully controls drivers for macOS.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] But if Apple allows, our engineers are ready and eager to help Apple deliver great drivers for macOS 10.14 (Mojave)." In October, Nvidia followed this up with another public announcement, "Apple fully controls drivers for macOS.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Unfortunately, Nvidia currently cannot release a driver unless it is approved by Apple," suggesting a possible rift between the two companies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] By January 2019, with still no sign of the enabling web drivers, Apple Insider weighed into the controversy with a claim that Apple management "doesn't want Nvidia support in macOS".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The following month, Apple Insider followed this up with another claim that Nvidia support was abandoned because of "relational issues in the past", and that Apple was developing its own GPU technology.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Without Apple-approved Nvidia web drivers, Apple users are faced with replacing their Nvidia cards with a competing supported brand, such as AMD Radeon from the list recommended by Apple.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On March 11, 2019, Nvidia announced a deal to buy Mellanox Technologies for $6.9 billion to substantially expand its footprint in the high-performance computing market.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The acquisition of the Israeli firm, a longtime supplier to the Israeli military, led to the 2023 launch of "Israel-1," described as the country's most powerful AI supercomputer.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2019, Nvidia announced new RTX Studio laptops.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The creators said that the new laptop was going to be seven times faster than a top-end MacBook Pro with a Core i9 and AMD's Radeon Pro Vega 20 graphics in apps like Maya and RedCine-X Pro.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In August 2019, Nvidia announced *Minecraft RTX*, an official Nvidia-developed patch for the game *Minecraft* adding real-time DXR ray tracing exclusively to the Windows 10 version of the game.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The whole game was, in Nvidia's words, "refit" with path tracing, which dramatically affects the way light, reflections, and shadows work inside the engine.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2020, Nvidia announced it was acquiring Cumulus Networks.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Post acquisition the company was absorbed into Nvidia's networking business unit, along with Mellanox.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2020, Nvidia developed an open-source ventilator to address the shortage resulting from the global coronavirus pandemic.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On May 14, 2020, Nvidia officially announced its Ampere GPU microarchitecture and the Nvidia A100 GPU accelerator.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In July 2020, it was reported that Nvidia was in talks with SoftBank to buy Arm, a UK-based chip designer, for $32 billion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On September 1, 2020, Nvidia officially announced the GeForce 30 series based on the company's new Ampere microarchitecture.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On September 13, 2020, Nvidia announced that it would buy Arm from SoftBank Group for $40 billion, subject to the usual scrutiny, with the latter retaining a 10% share of Nvidia.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In October 2020, Nvidia announced its plan to build the most powerful computer in Cambridge, England.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The computer, called Cambridge-1, launched in July 2021 with a $100 million investment and will employ AI to support healthcare research.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Also in October 2020, along with the release of the Nvidia RTX A6000, Nvidia announced it was retiring its workstation GPU brand Quadro, shifting its product name to Nvidia RTX for future products and the manufacturing to be Ampere architecture-based.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In August 2021, the proposed takeover of Arm was stalled after the UK's Competition and Markets Authority raised "significant competition concerns".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In October 2021, the European Commission opened a competition investigation into the takeover.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The Commission stated that Nvidia's acquisition could restrict competitors' access to Arm's products and provide Nvidia with too much internal information on its competitors due to their deals with Arm.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] SoftBank (the parent company of Arm) and Nvidia announced in early February 2022 that they "had agreed not to move forward with the transaction 'because of significant regulatory challenges'".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The investigation was set to end on March 15, 2022.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] That same month, Nvidia was reportedly compromised by a cyberattack.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This would have been the largest semiconductor acquisition in history.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In March 2022, Nvidia's CEO Jensen Huang mentioned that they were open to having Intel manufacture their chips in the future.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This was the first time the company mentioned that it would work together with Intel's upcoming foundry services.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In April 2022, it was reported that Nvidia planned to open a new research center in Yerevan, Armenia.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2022, Nvidia opened Voyager, the second of the two giant buildings at its new headquarters complex to the west of the old one.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Unlike its smaller and older sibling Endeavor, the triangle theming is used more "sparingly" in Voyager.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In September 2022, Nvidia announced its next-generation automotive-grade chip, Drive Thor.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In September 2022, Nvidia announced a collaboration with the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard related to the entire suite of Nvidia's AI-powered healthcare software suite called Clara, that includes Parabricks and MONAI.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Following United States Department of Commerce regulations which placed an embargo on exports to China of advanced microchips, which went into effect in October 2022, Nvidia saw its data center chip added to the export control list.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The next month, the company unveiled a new advanced chip in China, called the A800 GPU, that met the export control rules.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In September 2023, Getty Images announced that it was partnering with Nvidia to launch Generative AI by Getty Images, a new tool that let people create images using Getty's library of licensed photos.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Getty said they would use Nvidia's Edify model, which was available on Nvidia's generative AI model library Picasso.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On September 26, 2023, Denny's CEO Kelli Valade joined Huang in East San Jose to celebrate the founding of Nvidia at Denny's on Berryessa Road, where a plaque was installed to mark the relevant corner booth as the birthplace of a $1 trillion company.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] By then, Nvidia's H100 GPUs were in such demand that even other tech giants were beholden to how Nvidia allocated supply.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Larry Ellison of Oracle Corporation said that month that during a dinner with Huang at Nobu in Palo Alto, he and Elon Musk of Tesla, Inc. and xAI "were begging" for H100s, "I guess is the best way to describe it.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In October 2023, it was reported that Nvidia had quietly begun designing ARM-based central processing units (CPUs) for Microsoft's Windows operating system with a target to start selling them in 2025.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In January 2024, *Forbes* reported that Nvidia has increased its lobbying presence in Washington, D.C. as American lawmakers consider proposals to regulate artificial intelligence.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] From 2023 to 2024, the company reportedly hired at least four government affairs with professional backgrounds at agencies including the United States Department of State and the Department of the Treasury.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] It was noted that the $350,000 spent by the company on lobbying in 2023 was small compared to a number of major tech companies in the artificial intelligence space.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In January 2024, Raymond James Financial analysts estimated that Nvidia was selling the H100 GPU in the price range of $25,000 to $30,000 each, while on eBay, individual H100s cost over $40,000.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Several major technology companies were purchasing tens or hundreds of thousands of GPUs for their data centers to run generative artificial intelligence projects; simple arithmetic implied that they were committing to billions of dollars in capital expenditures.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In February 2024, it was reported that Nvidia was the "hot employer" in Silicon Valley because it was offering interesting work and good pay at a time when other tech employers were downsizing.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Half of Nvidia employees earned over $228,000 in 2023.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] By then, Nvidia GPUs had become so valuable that they needed special security while in transit to data centers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Cisco chief information officer Fletcher Previn explained at a CIO summit: "Those GPUs arrive by armored car".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On March 1, 2024, Nvidia became the third company in the history of the United States to close with a market capitalization in excess of $2 trillion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia needed only 180 days to get to $2 trillion from $1 trillion, while the first two companies, Apple and Microsoft, each took over 500 days.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On March 18, Nvidia announced its new AI chip and microarchitecture Blackwell, named after mathematician David Blackwell.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In April 2024, Reuters reported that China had allegedly acquired banned Nvidia chips and servers from Supermicro and Dell via tenders.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In June 2024, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) and the Justice Department (DOJ) began antitrust investigations into Nvidia, Microsoft and OpenAI, focusing on their influence in the AI industry.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The FTC led the investigations into Microsoft and OpenAI, while the DOJ handled Nvidia.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The probes centered on the companies' conduct rather than mergers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This development followed an open letter from OpenAI employees expressing concerns about the rapid AI advancements and lack of oversight.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The company became the world's most valuable, surpassing Microsoft and Apple, on June 18, 2024, after its market capitalization exceeded $3.3 trillion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In June 2024, Trend Micro announced a partnership with Nvidia to develop AI-driven security tools, notably to protect the data centers where AI workloads are processed.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This collaboration integrates Nvidia NIM and Nvidia Morpheus with Trend Vision One and its Sovereign and Private Cloud solutions to improve data privacy, real-time analysis, and rapid threat mitigation.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In October 2024, Nvidia introduced a family of open-source multimodal large language models called NVLM 1.0, which features a flagship version with 72 billion parameters, designed to improve text-only performance after multimodal training.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In October 2024, Nvidia reported that it had been collaborating with Raytheon (a RTX Corporation business) to “explore network pipelines that accelerate workloads on GPUs and use GPU acceleration software libraries”.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In November 2024, the company was added to the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In November 2024, Morgan Stanley reported that "the entire 2025 production" of all of Nvidia's Blackwell chips was "already sold out".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Also in November 2024, the company bought 1.2 million shares of Nebius Group.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia was ranked #3 on Forbes' "Best Places to Work" list in 2024.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As of January 7, 2025, Nvidia's $3.66 trillion market cap was worth more than double of the combined value of AMD, ARM, Broadcom, and Intel.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In January 2025, Nvidia saw the largest one-day loss in market capitalization for a U.S. company in history at $600 billion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This was due to DeepSeek, a Chinese AI startup that developed an advanced AI model at a lower cost and computing power.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] DeepSeek's AI assistant, using the V3 model, surpassed ChatGPT as the highest-rated free app in the U.S. on Apple's App Store.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On April 7, 2025, Nvidia released the Llama-3.1-Nemotron-Ultra-253B-v1 reasoning large language model, under the Nvidia Open Model License.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] It comes in three sizes: Nano, Super and Ultra.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On May 28, 2025, Nvidia's second-quarter revenue forecast fell short of market estimates due to U.S. export restrictions impacting AI chip sales to China, yet the company's stock rose 5% as investors remained optimistic about long-term AI demand.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In July 2025, it was announced that Nvidia had acquired CentML, a Canadian-based AI firm.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On July 10, 2025, Nvidia closed for the first time with a market cap above $4 trillion, after its market cap briefly touched and then retreated from that number during the previous day.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia became the first company to reach a market cap of $4 trillion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] At that point, Nvidia was worth more than the combined value of all publicly traded companies in the United Kingdom.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On July 29, 2025, Nvidia ordered 300,000 H20 AI chips from Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC) due to strong demand from Chinese tech firms like Tencent and Alibaba.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In August 2025, Nvidia and competitor Advanced Micro Devices agreed to pay 15% of the revenues from certain chip sales in China as part of an arrangement to obtain export licenses.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia will pay only for sales of the H20 chips.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] China's internet regulator banned the country's largest technology companies from buying Nvidia's artificial intelligence chips as part of efforts to strengthen the domestic industry and compete with the United States.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The CAC instructed companies this week to end both testing and orders of the RTX Pro 6000D, which Nvidia had designed as a tailor-made product for China, according to three people with knowledge of the matter.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On September 18, 2025, Nvidia announced it would invest $5 billion in Intel, backing the struggling U.S. chipmaker just weeks after the White House arranged a deal for the federal government to take a major stake in the company.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The investment will give Nvidia an immediate holding of about 4% in Intel once new shares are issued to finalize the agreement.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's move provides Intel with fresh support following years of unsuccessful turnaround efforts and will allow Nvidia to offer its powerful GB300 data center servers based on Blackwell GPUs on Intel's X86 architecture.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On September 22, 2025, Nvidia and OpenAI announced a memorandum of understanding for a partnership wherein Nvidia would invest $100 billion into OpenAI, and OpenAI would use Nvidia chips and systems in new data centers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] OpenAI will build new AI data centers using Nvidia systems, amounting to at least 10 gigawatts system power, which is the equivalent of energy produced by more than four Hoover Dams.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The deal was meant to be a circular arrangement where OpenAI will pay back Nvidia's investment through the purchase of Nvidia's chips, which is a model common in AI partnerships.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This "circularity" is estimated at $35 billion in new Nvidia chips bought by OpenAI, for every $10 billion Nvidia invests in OpenAI.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As of January 2026, negotiations had not progressed beyond early stages, and the two companies were rethinking the partnership's structure.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In the months leading up to this, chief executive Jensen Huang privately emphasized to industry associates that the original deal was non-binding and not finalized when announced.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Dubbed "Aurora", the facility is expected to set a new flexible power standard.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] A server farm dedicated to autonomous AI was also announced in October 2025, as a collaboration between SDS Schönfeld, a data services firm owned by UC Schönfeld, and VAST Data, an Israeli company specializing in AI storage management that collaborates closely with Nvidia.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Reports indicate that approximately $30 billion has been secured for the Bet Yehoshua server farm.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On October 29, 2025, Nvidia became the first company to reach a market capitalization of $5 trillion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's stock prices fell by 2% on November 11, 2025, as the SoftBank Group dumped its entire Nvidia portfolio worth $5.8 billion, redirecting the capital towards OpenAI instead.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On December 1, 2025, Nvidia released Alpamayo-R1, an open source, vision-language-action AI model for self-driving vehicles.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] This was done so that developers and researchers can understand how these models work and come up with standard ways on how the industry can evaluate how they work.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On December 15, 2025, Nvidia announced the Nemotron 3 family of models consisting of Nano, Super and Ultra models, built on a hybrid mixture-of-experts (MoE) architecture.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia said Nano has around 30 billion parameters, Super 100 billion, and Ultra 500 billion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On December 18, 2025, Nvidia announced plans to build a major new research and development campus in Kiryat Tivon, Israel, projected to employ more than 10,000 people and become one of the company's largest sites outside the United States.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The 22-acre complex is scheduled to begin construction in 2027, with initial operations expected in 2031, and will include laboratories, green areas, and public facilities.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The project reinforces Israel's role as Nvidia's principal international development hub in advanced AI and computing technologies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In December 2025, it was announced that Nvidia had acquired SchedMD, the company behind the open-source workload manager Slurm, as part of an effort to expand its AI and high-performance computing software capabilities.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia stated that Slurm would remain open-source and vendor-neutral after the acquisition, with no financial terms disclosed.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In December 2025, CNBC reported Nvidia had agreed to buy assets from Groq for $20 billion in cash.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The deal included a non-exclusive licensing agreement with Nvidia for Groq's inference technology.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Several of Groq's senior leaders, including its CEO, also agreed to join Nvidia as part of the deal.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] While both companies said Groq would continue to operate as an individual company, the transaction drew criticism from several industry analysts as a tactic to avoid regulatory scrutiny.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In late 2025, Nvidia entered advanced negotiations to acquire AI21 Labs, an Israeli developer of large language models, in a deal valued at as much as $2 billion to $3 billion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The proposed transaction is widely described as a talent-focused "acquihire" aimed at integrating AI21's workforce of approximately 200 specialists into Nvidia's global artificial intelligence operations.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] If completed, the transaction would be Nvidia's second-largest Israeli acquisition after its $7 billion purchase of Mellanox in 2020.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] At CES 2026, CEO Jensen Huang unveiled Nvidia's Vera Rubin AI platform and the Alpamayo open-source model.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Hesai was also picked as Nvidia's laser technology partner, supplying Lidar sensors to the company, streamlining software, hardware, and data in its autonomous driving products.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In January 2026, Nvidia launched a new weather forecasting service called Earth-2.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] It is an open-sourced platform that can be incorporated to improve the AI function across models used by scientists, businesses and local governments.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On February 24, 2026, Nvidia announced its acquisition of Israeli startup Illumex, a developer of generative semantic data infrastructure, in a deal reportedly valued at around $60 million.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On March 11, 2026, Nvidia announced that it will invest $2 billion in artificial intelligence cloud company Nebius.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In April 2026, Nvidia announced the release of a new group of open-source artificial intelligence models designed specifically for quantum computing.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The development caused a noticeable market surge for allied quantum computing companies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] During the same month, Nvidia's market momentum was further bolstered by its primary manufacturing partner, TSMC, which reported a 35.1% year-on-year revenue increase for the first quarter of 2026, largely driven by robust global demand for AI accelerators.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] At the GTC conference in March 2026, Nvidia announced the "Vera Rubin" platform, the successor to its Blackwell architecture.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The platform includes the Rubin GPU and Vera CPU, designed to scale "agentic AI" and offering significant performance improvements in large-scale AI factories.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In May 2026, Nvidia announced that it would be partnering with Corning and investing up to 3.2 billion to build 3 new advanced manufacturing facilities in North Carolina and Texas as part of a optical fiber deal.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On June 1, 2026, Nvidia released the RTX Spark chip intended for laptops.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] For the fiscal year 2020, Nvidia reported earnings of US$2.796 billion, with an annual revenue of US$10.918 billion, a decline of 6.8% over the previous fiscal cycle.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's shares traded at over $531 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at over US$328.7 billion in January 2021.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] For the Q2 of 2020, Nvidia reported sales of $3.87 billion, which was a 50% rise from the same period in 2019.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The surge in sales was driven by people's higher demand for computer technology.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia uses external suppliers for all phases of manufacturing, including wafer fabrication, assembly, testing, and packaging.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia thus avoids most of the investment and production costs and risks associated with chip manufacturing, although it does sometimes directly procure some components and materials used in the production of its products (e.g., memory and substrates).
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia focuses its own resources on product design, quality assurance, marketing, and customer support.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia's GPU Technology Conference (GTC) is a series of technical conferences held around the world.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] It originated in 2009 in San Jose, California, with an initial focus on the potential for solving computing challenges through GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In recent years, the conference's focus has shifted to various applications of artificial intelligence and deep learning; including self-driving cars, healthcare, high-performance computing, and Nvidia Deep Learning Institute (DLI) training.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] GTC 2020 was converted to a digital event and drew roughly 59,000 registrants.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] After several years of remote-only events, GTC in March 2024 returned to an in-person format in San Jose, California.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] At GTC 2025, Nvidia unveiled its next-generation AI hardware, the Blackwell Ultra and Vera Rubin chips, signalling a leap toward agentic AI and reasoning-capable computing.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Huang projected that AI-driven infrastructure would drive Nvidia's data center revenue to $1 trillion by 2028.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The announcement also introduced Isaac GR00T N1 (humanoid robotics model), Cosmos (synthetic training data AI), and the Newton physics engine, developed in collaboration with DeepMind and Disney Research.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Until September 23, 2013, Nvidia had not published any documentation for its advanced hardware, meaning that programmers could not write free and open-source device drivers for its products without resorting to reverse engineering.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Additionally, features like its compute platform CUDA and the DLSS technology suite are proprietary and only available on its hardware.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As such, Nvidia has been notable for proprietization and vendor-locking practices.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Instead, Nvidia provides its own binary GeForce graphics drivers for X.Org and an open-source library that interfaces with the Linux, FreeBSD or Solaris kernels and the proprietary graphics software.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia also provided but stopped supporting an obfuscated open-source driver that only supports two-dimensional hardware acceleration and ships with the X.Org distribution.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] The proprietary nature of Nvidia's drivers has generated dissatisfaction within free-software communities.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In a 2012 talk, Linus Torvalds gave a middle-finger gesture and criticized Nvidia's stance toward Linux.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Nvidia only provides x86/x64 and ARMv7-A versions of its proprietary driver; as a result, features like CUDA are unavailable on other platforms.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Some users claim that Nvidia's Linux drivers impose artificial restrictions, like limiting the number of monitors that can be used at the same time, but the company has not commented on these accusations.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] In 2014, with its Maxwell GPUs, Nvidia started to require firmware by it to unlock all features of its graphics cards.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On May 12, 2022, Nvidia announced that it is opensourcing its GPU kernel modules.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] Support for Nvidia's firmware was implemented in nouveau in 2023, which allows proper power management and GPU reclocking for Turing and newer graphics card generations.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] On July 21, 2025, Nvidia announced to extend CUDA support to RISC-V.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p01] As of 2026, NVIDIA has over a 100 different open-source projects available on GitHub in different areas such as computer vision, networking, cybersecurity, AR/VR, Robotics, Generative AI etc.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia GPUs are used in deep learning, and accelerated analytics due to Nvidia's CUDA software platform and API which allows programmers to utilize the higher number of cores present in GPUs to parallelize BLAS operations which are extensively used in machine learning algorithms.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] They were included in many Tesla, Inc. vehicles before Musk announced at Tesla Autonomy Day in 2019 that the company developed its own SoC and full self-driving computer now and would stop using Nvidia hardware for their vehicles.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] These GPUs are used by researchers, laboratories, tech companies and enterprise companies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2009, Nvidia was involved in what was called the "big bang" of deep learning, "as deep-learning neural networks were combined with Nvidia graphics processing units (GPUs)".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] That year, the Google Brain team used Nvidia GPUs to create deep neural networks capable of machine learning, where Andrew Ng determined that GPUs could increase the speed of deep learning systems by about 100 times.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] DGX is a line of supercomputers by Nvidia.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In April 2016, Nvidia produced the DGX-1 based on an 8 GPU cluster, to improve the ability of users to use deep learning by combining GPUs with integrated deep learning software.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia gifted its first DGX-1 to OpenAI in August 2016 to help it train larger and more complex AI models with the capability of reducing processing time from six days to two hours.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] It also developed Nvidia Tesla K80 and P100 GPU-based virtual machines, which are available through Google Cloud, which Google installed in November 2016.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Microsoft added GPU servers in a preview offering of its N series based on Nvidia's Tesla K80s, each containing 4992 processing cores.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Later that year, AWS's P2 instance was produced using up to 16 Nvidia Tesla K80 GPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] That month Nvidia also partnered with IBM to create a software kit that boosts the AI capabilities of Watson, called IBM PowerAI.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia also offers its own Nvidia Deep Learning software development kit.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2017, the GPUs were also brought online at the Riken Center for Advanced Intelligence Project for Fujitsu.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The company's deep learning technology led to a boost in its 2017 earnings.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2018, Nvidia researchers demonstrated imitation-learning techniques for industrial robots.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] They have created a system that, after a short revision and testing, can already be used to control the universal robots of the next generation.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In addition to GPU manufacturing, Nvidia provides parallel processing capabilities to researchers and scientists that allow them to efficiently run high-performance applications.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2020, Nvidia unveiled "Omniverse", a virtual environment designed for engineers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia also open-sourced Isaac Sim, which makes use of this Omniverse to train robots through simulations that mimic the physics of the robots and the real world.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2024, Huang oriented Nvidia's focus towards humanoid robots and self-driving cars, which he expects to gain widespread adoption.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2025, Nvidia announced Isaac GR00T N1, an open-source foundation model "designed to expedite the development and capabilities of humanoid robots".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Neura Robotics, 1X Technologies and Vention are among the first companies to use the model.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] NVIDIA has been involves in the automotive industry since introducing NVIDIA drive in CES 2015.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In April 2021, NVIDIA announced "DRIVE Sim" - A simulation platform for autonomous vehicles based on the Omniverse platform, which according to NVIDIA brought high fidelity, and was much more physically accurate and fully repeatable which is required for V&V.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In January 2026, NVIDIA announced Alpamayo, "family of open AI models, simulation tools and datasets designed to accelerate the next era of safe, reasoning‑based autonomous vehicle (AV) development.".
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia's Inception Program was created to support startups making exceptional advances in the fields of artificial intelligence and data science.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Award winners are announced at Nvidia's GTC Conference.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In May 2017, the program had 1,300 companies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] As of March 2018, there were 2,800 startups in the Inception Program.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] As of August 2021, the program has over 8,500 members in 90 countries, with cumulative funding of US$60 billion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Issues with the GeForce GTX 970's specifications were first brought up by users when they found out that the cards, while featuring 4 GB of memory, rarely accessed memory over the 3.5 GB boundary.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The card's back-end hardware specifications, initially announced as being identical to those of the GeForce GTX 980, differed in the amount of L2 cache (1.75 MB versus 2 MB in the GeForce GTX 980) and the number of ROPs (56 versus 64 in the 980).
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Additionally, it was revealed that the card was designed to access its memory as a 3.5 GB section, plus a 0.5 GB one, access to the latter being 7 times slower than the first one.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The company then went on to promise a specific driver modification to alleviate the performance issues produced by the cutbacks suffered by the card.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] However, Nvidia later clarified that the promise had been a miscommunication and there would be no specific driver update for the GTX 970.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia claimed that it would assist customers who wanted refunds in obtaining them.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] On February 26, 2015, Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang went on record in Nvidia's official blog to apologize for the incident.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In February 2015 a class-action lawsuit alleging false advertising was filed against Nvidia and Gigabyte Technology in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia revealed that it is able to disable individual units, each containing 256 KB of L2 cache and 8 ROPs, without disabling whole memory controllers.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] This is used in the GeForce GTX 970, which therefore can be described as having 3.5 GB in its high speed segment on a 224-bit bus and 0.5 GB in a low speed segment on a 32-bit bus.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] On July 27, 2016, Nvidia agreed to a preliminary settlement of the U.S. class action lawsuit, offering a $30 refund on GTX 970 purchases.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The agreed upon refund represents the portion of the cost of the storage and performance capabilities the consumers assumed they were obtaining when they purchased the card.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The Nvidia GeForce Partner Program was a marketing program designed to provide partnering companies with benefits such as public relations support, video game bundling, and marketing development funds.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The program proved to be controversial, with complaints about it possibly being an anti-competitive practice.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] First announced in a blog post on March 1, 2018, it was canceled on May 4, 2018.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] On December 10, 2020, Nvidia told YouTube tech reviewer Steven Walton of Hardware Unboxed that it would no longer supply him with GeForce Founders Edition graphics card review units.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In a Twitter message, Hardware Unboxed said, "Nvidia have officially decided to ban us from receiving GeForce Founders Edition GPU review samples.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Their reasoning is that we are focusing on rasterization instead of ray tracing.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] A number of technology reviewers came out strongly against Nvidia's move.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Linus Sebastian, of Linus Tech Tips, titled the episode of his weekly WAN Show, "NVIDIA might ACTUALLY be EVIL..." and was highly critical of the company's move to dictate specific outcomes of technology reviews.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The review site Gamers Nexus said it was, "Nvidia's latest decision to shoot both its feet: They've now made it so that any reviewers covering RT will become subject to scrutiny from untrusting viewers who will suspect subversion by the company.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Two days later, Nvidia reversed its stance.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Hardware Unboxed sent out a Twitter message, "I just received an email from Nvidia apologizing for the previous email & they've now walked everything back." On December 14, Hardware Unboxed released a video explaining the controversy from their viewpoint.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2018, Nvidia's chips became popular for cryptomining, the process of obtaining crypto rewards in exchange for verifying transactions on distributed ledgers, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) said.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] However, the company failed to disclose that it was a "significant element" of its revenue growth from sales of chips designed for gaming, the SEC further added in a statement and charging order.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Those omissions misled investors and analysts who were interested in understanding the impact of cryptomining on Nvidia's business, the SEC emphasized.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia, which did not admit or deny the findings, has agreed to pay $5.5 million to settle civil charges, according to a statement made by the SEC in May 2022.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] On September 26, 2023, Nvidia's French offices were searched by the French Competition Authority.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The raid, authorized by a judge, was part of an investigation into suspected anti-competitive practices in the graphics card sector.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia has not publicly commented on the incident.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In August 2025, Nvidia ordered suppliers to halt production of its H20 AI chip following Chinese government directives warning domestic companies against purchasing the processor due to security concerns.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The company directed suppliers including Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, Samsung Electronics, and Amkor Technology to suspend work on the China-focused processor.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The H20 was developed in late 2023 specifically for the Chinese market to comply with U.S. export restrictions, featuring 96GB of HBM3 memory and 4.0 TB/s memory bandwidth-higher than the H100-but with significantly reduced computational power at 296 TFLOPs compared to the H100's 1979 TFLOPs.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Despite lower raw performance, the H20 demonstrated over 20% faster performance than the H100 in large language model inference tasks due to architectural optimizations.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Prior to the production halt, Nvidia had placed substantial orders for the H20, including 300,000 units from TSMC in July 2025, driven by strong demand from Chinese technology companies.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Despite China's efforts to shape technical standards, still, American products and ecosystem retain strong appeal, raising government experts concern.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] CEO Jensen Huang denied allegations that the H20 contained security backdoors, stating the chips were designed solely for commercial use.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The production suspension occurred as Nvidia was developing the B30A, a new chip based on its Blackwell architecture intended to succeed the H20 in the Chinese market.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Despite criticism, the United States announced in 2026 that it would permit the export of newer H200 chips to China under specified conditions.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The move was expected to stimulate market activity and U.S. influence.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] The Chinese market, estimated to be worth hundreds of billions and potentially trillions of U.S. dollars, presents significant profit opportunities for American firms, with revenues reinforcing leading positions.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] However, China quickly responded by imposing restrictions on certain foreign chips to be imported.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] China is leveraging the sanction to advance its domestic technology sector, while concerns have also emerged over possible fragmentation and reduced reinvestment in its own artificial intelligence development.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] China’s refusal to buy them could cost the company $30 billion.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia has been involved in heavy data scraping for illegal AI model training.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In 2024, internal conversations revealed that Nvidia was scraping large amounts of videos from YouTube without permission, and by circumventing protection measures.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] In January 2026, a court filing revealed that Nvidia developers contacted shadow library Anna's Archive to evaluate the use of pirated content for model training, which management gave green light for despite legality concerns from the site.
[src:cuda-programming/nvidia-p02] Nvidia denied the allegations and filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] In computer science, a **parallel algorithm**, as opposed to a traditional serial algorithm, is an algorithm which can do multiple operations in a given time.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] It has been a tradition of computer science to describe serial algorithms in abstract machine models, often the one known as random-access machine.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Similarly, many computer science researchers have used a so-called parallel random-access machine (PRAM) as a parallel abstract machine (shared-memory).
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Many parallel algorithms are executed concurrently – though in general concurrent algorithms are a distinct concept – and thus these concepts are often conflated, with which aspect of an algorithm is parallel and which is concurrent not being clearly distinguished.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Further, non-parallel, non-concurrent algorithms are often referred to as "sequential algorithms", by contrast with concurrent algorithms.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Algorithms vary significantly in how parallelizable they are, ranging from easily parallelizable to completely unparallelizable.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Further, a given problem may accommodate different algorithms, which may be more or less parallelizable.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Some problems are easy to divide up into pieces in this way – these are called *embarrassingly parallel problems.* Examples include many algorithms to solve Rubik's Cubes and find values which result in a given hash.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Some problems cannot be split up into parallel portions, as they require the results from a preceding step to effectively carry on with the next step – these are called **inherently serial problems**.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Examples include iterative numerical methods, such as Newton's method, iterative solutions to the three-body problem, and most of the available algorithms to compute pi (π).
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Some sequential algorithms can be converted into parallel algorithms using automatic parallelization.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] In many cases developing an effective parallel algorithm to solve a task requires developing new ideas and methods not needed in the design of a sequential algorithm to solve the same problem.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Examples of such cases include the practically important problems of searching for a target element in a data structure and the evaluation of an algebraic expression.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Parallel algorithms on individual devices have become more common since the early 2000s because of substantial improvements in multiprocessing systems and the rise of multi-core processors.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Up until the end of 2004, single-core processor performance rapidly increased via frequency scaling, and thus it was easier to construct a computer with a single fast core than one with many slower cores with the same throughput, so multicore systems were of more limited use.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Since 2004 however, frequency scaling hit a wall, and thus multicore systems have become more widespread, making parallel algorithms of more general use.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] The cost or complexity of serial algorithms is estimated in terms of the space (memory) and time (processor cycles) that they take.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Parallel algorithms need to optimize one more resource, the communication between different processors.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] There are two ways parallel processors communicate, shared memory or message passing.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Shared memory processing needs additional locking for the data, imposes the overhead of additional processor and bus cycles, and also serializes some portion of the algorithm.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Message passing processing uses channels and message boxes but this communication adds transfer overhead on the bus, additional memory need for queues and message boxes and latency in the messages.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Designs of parallel processors use special buses like crossbar so that the communication overhead will be small but it is the parallel algorithm that decides the volume of the traffic.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] If the communication overhead of additional processors outweighs the benefit of adding another processor, one encounters parallel slowdown.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Another problem with parallel algorithms is ensuring that they are suitably load balanced, by ensuring that *load* (overall work) is balanced, rather than input size being balanced.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] A subtype of parallel algorithms, *distributed algorithms*, are algorithms designed to work in cluster computing and distributed computing environments, where additional concerns beyond the scope of "classical" parallel algorithms need to be addressed.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Distributed algorithms are intended to run on a network of interconnected computers that communicate through shared memory or message passing.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Unlike traditional parallel algorithms, they must operate under additional constraints such as limited local knowledge, communication delays, the lack of a global state, and the possibility of node failures.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] The focus of distributed algorithms is on coordination problems that arise in distributed systems, including leader election, mutual exclusion, and consensus (computer science).
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] These problems are studied under different system models with varying assumptions, such as whether the system is synchronous or asynchronous and if there are failures, such as crash failures or Byzantine failures.
[src:cuda-programming/parallel-algorithm] Distributed algorithms have many practical applications in distributed databases, fault-tolerance systems, and large-scale networked applications.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Such machines exploit data level parallelism, but not concurrency: there are simultaneous (parallel) computations, but each unit performs exactly the same instruction at any given moment (just with different data).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] A simple example is to add many pairs of numbers together, all of the SIMD units are performing an addition, but each one has different pairs of values to add.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SIMD is especially applicable to common tasks such as adjusting the contrast in a digital image or adjusting the volume of digital audio.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Most modern central processing unit (CPU) designs include SIMD instructions to improve the performance of multimedia use.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] In recent CPUs, SIMD units are tightly coupled with cache hierarchies and prefetch mechanisms, which minimize latency during large block operations.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] For instance, AVX-512-enabled processors can prefetch entire cache lines and apply fused multiply-add operations (FMA) in a single SIMD cycle.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SIMD has three different subcategories in Flynn's 1972 Taxonomy, one of which is single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SIMT should not be confused with software threads or hardware threads, both of which are task time-sharing (time-slicing).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SIMT is true simultaneous parallel hardware-level execution, such as in the ILLIAC IV.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SIMD should not be confused with Vector processing, characterized by the Cray 1 and clarified in Duncan's taxonomy.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The difference between SIMD and vector processors is primarily the presence of a Cray-style `SET VECTOR LENGTH` instruction.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The first known operational use to date of SIMD within a register was the TX-2, in 1958.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It was capable of 36-bit operations and two 18-bit or four 9-bit sub-word operations.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The first commercial use of SIMD instructions was in the ILLIAC IV, which was completed in 1972.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Vector supercomputers of the early 1970s such as the CDC Star-100 and the Texas Instruments ASC could operate on a "vector" of data with a single instruction.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Vector processing was especially popularized by Cray in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Vector processing architectures are now considered separate from SIMD computers: Duncan's Taxonomy includes them whereas Flynn's Taxonomy does not, due to Flynn's work (1966, 1972) pre-dating the Cray-1 (1977).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The complexity of Vector processors however inspired a simpler arrangement known as SIMD within a register.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The first era of modern SIMD computers was characterized by massively parallel processing-style supercomputers such as the Thinking Machines Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] These computers had many limited-functionality processors that would work in parallel.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] For example, each of 65,536 single-bit processors in a Thinking Machines CM-2 would execute the same instruction at the same time, allowing, for instance, to logically combine 65,536 pairs of bits at a time, using a hypercube-connected network or processor-dedicated RAM to find its operands.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Supercomputing moved away from the SIMD approach when inexpensive scalar multiple instruction, multiple data (MIMD) approaches based on commodity processors such as the Intel i860 XP became more powerful, and interest in SIMD waned.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The current era of SIMD processors grew out of the desktop-computer market rather than the supercomputer market.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] As desktop processors became powerful enough to support real-time gaming and audio/video processing during the 1990s, demand grew for this type of computing power, and microprocessor vendors turned to SIMD to meet the demand.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This resurgence also coincided with the rise of DirectX and OpenGL shader models, which heavily leveraged SIMD under the hood.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The graphics APIs encouraged programmers to adopt data-parallel programming styles, indirectly accelerating SIMD adoption in desktop software.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Hewlett-Packard introduced Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) instructions into PA-RISC 1.1 desktops in 1994 to accelerate MPEG decoding.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Sun Microsystems introduced SIMD integer instructions in its "VIS" instruction set extensions in 1995, in its UltraSPARC I microprocessor.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] MIPS followed suit with their similar MDMX system.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The first widely deployed desktop SIMD was with Intel's MMX extensions to the x86 architecture in 1996.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This sparked the introduction of the much more powerful AltiVec system in the Motorola PowerPC and IBM's POWER systems.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Intel responded in 1999 by introducing the all-new SSE system.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Since then, there have been several extensions to the SIMD instruction sets for both architectures.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Advanced vector extensions AVX, AVX2 and AVX-512 are developed by Intel.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] AMD supports AVX, AVX2, and AVX-512 in their current products.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] With SIMD, an order of magnitude increase in code size is not uncommon, when compared to equivalent scalar or equivalent vector code, and an order of magnitude *or greater* effectiveness (work done per instruction) is achievable with Vector ISAs.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] ARM's Scalable Vector Extension takes another approach, known in Flynn's Taxonomy more commonly known today as "Predicated" (masked) SIMD.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This approach is not as compact as vector processing but is still far better than non-predicated SIMD.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Detailed comparative examples are given at Vector processor § Vector instruction example.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Small-scale (64 or 128 bits) SIMD became popular on general-purpose CPUs in the early 1990s and continued through 1997 and later with Motion Video Instructions (MVI) for Alpha.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Intel's AVX-512 SIMD instructions process 512 bits of data at once.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The IBM, Sony, Toshiba co-developed Cell processor's Synergistic Processing Element's (SPE's) instruction set is heavily SIMD based.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] AMD GPUs since the TeraScale (microarchitecture) are SIMD-based, a feature that has remained in the 2020s microartectures RDNA and CDNA, with a layer of single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT) above.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] On the other hand, Nvidia's CUDA architectures use scalar cores with SIMT.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Philips, now NXP, developed several SIMD processors named Xetal.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The Xetal has 320 16-bit processor elements especially designed for vision tasks.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Apple's M1 and M2 chips also incorporate SIMD units deeply integrated with their GPU and Neural Engine, using Apple-designed SIMD pipelines optimized for image filtering, convolution, and matrix multiplication.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This unified memory architecture helps SIMD instructions operate on shared memory pools more efficiently.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] (The CPU part implements ordinary NEON).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SIMD instructions are widely used to process 3D graphics, although modern graphics cards with embedded SIMD have largely taken over this task from the CPU.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Some systems also include permute functions that re-pack elements inside vectors, making them especially useful for data processing and compression.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The trend of general-purpose computing on GPUs (GPGPU) may lead to wider use of SIMD in the future.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Recent compilers such as LLVM, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), and Intel's ICC offer aggressive auto-vectoring options.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Developers can often enable these with flags like `-O3` or `-ftree-vectorize`, which guide the compiler to restructure loops for SIMD compatibility.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Adoption of SIMD systems in personal computer software was at first slow, due to a number of problems.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] One was that many of the early SIMD instruction sets tended to slow overall performance of the system due to the re-use of existing floating point registers.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Other systems, like MMX and 3DNow!, offered support for data types that were not interesting to a wide audience and had expensive context switching instructions to switch between using the FPU and MMX registers.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Compilers also often lacked support, requiring programmers to resort to assembly language coding.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The introduction of 3DNow! by AMD and SSE by Intel confused matters somewhat, but today the system seems to have settled down (after AMD adopted SSE) and newer compilers should result in more SIMD-enabled software.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Intel and AMD now both provide optimized math libraries that use SIMD instructions, and open source alternatives like libSIMD, SIMDx86 and SLEEF have started to appear (see also libm).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Apple Computer had somewhat more success, even though they entered the SIMD market later than the rest.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] AltiVec offered a rich system and can be programmed using increasingly sophisticated compilers from Motorola, IBM and GNU, therefore assembly language programming is rarely needed.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Additionally, many of the systems that would benefit from SIMD were supplied by Apple itself, for example iTunes and QuickTime.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] However, in 2006, Apple computers moved to Intel x86 processors.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Apple's APIs and development tools (XCode) were modified to support SSE2 and SSE3 as well as AltiVec.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Apple was the dominant purchaser of PowerPC chips from IBM and Freescale Semiconductor.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Even though Apple has stopped using PowerPC processors in their products, further development of AltiVec is continued in several PowerPC and Power ISA designs from Freescale and IBM.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It is common for publishers of the SIMD instruction sets to make their own C and C++ language extensions with intrinsic functions or special datatypes (with operator overloading) guaranteeing the generation of vector code.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Intel, AltiVec, and ARM NEON provide extensions widely adopted by the compilers targeting their CPUs.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The GNU C Compiler takes the extensions a step further by abstracting them into a universal interface that can be used on any platform by providing a way of defining SIMD datatypes.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The LLVM Clang compiler also implements the feature, with an analogous interface defined in the IR.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Rust's `packed_simd` crate (and the experimental `std::simd`) uses this interface, and so does Swift 2.0+.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] C++ has an experimental interface `std::experimental::simd` that works similarly to the GCC extension.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] For GCC and libstdc++, a wrapper library that builds on top of the GCC extension is available.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The `System.Numerics.Vector` package, available on NuGet, implements SIMD datatypes.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Java also has a new proposed API for SIMD instructions available in OpenJDK 17 in an incubator module.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It also has a safe fallback mechanism on unsupported CPUs to simple loops.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Instead of providing an SIMD datatype, compilers can also be hinted to auto-vectorize some loops, potentially taking some assertions about the lack of data dependency.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This is not as flexible as manipulating SIMD variables directly, but is easier to use.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] OpenMP 4.0+ has a `#pragma omp simd` hint.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This OpenMP interface has replaced a wide set of nonstandard extensions, including Cilk's `#pragma simd`, GCC's `#pragma GCC ivdep`, and many more.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] "SIMD everywhere", a collection of C/C++ headers implementing platform-specific intrinsics for other platforms (e.g.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] SSE intrinsics for ARM NEON), includes the use of platform-specific intrinsics, generic vector interfaces, and vectorization hints.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It can be used as a "Rosetta Stone" for comparing these different SIMD programming paradigms.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Another approach is SPMD: write a program that looks as if it operates only one element on the time, then have a compiler widen it to match the SIMD vector width.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This is the approach used by graphics shaders and more recently adopted by CPU-oriented tools such as Intel IPSC.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Consumer software is typically expected to work on a range of CPUs covering multiple generations, which could limit the programmer's ability to use new SIMD instructions to improve the computational performance of a program.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The solution is to include multiple versions of the same code that uses either older or newer SIMD technologies, and pick one that best fits the user's CPU at run-time (dynamic dispatch).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] FMV, manually coded in assembly language, is quite commonly used in a number of performance-critical libraries such as glibc and libjpeg-turbo.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Intel C++ Compiler, GNU Compiler Collection since GCC 6, and Clang since clang 7 allow for a simplified approach, with the compiler taking care of function duplication and selection.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] GCC and clang requires explicit `target_clones` labels in the code to "clone" functions, while ICC does so automatically (under the command-line option `/Qax`).
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The Rust programming language also supports FMV.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The setup is similar to GCC and Clang in that the code defines what instruction sets to compile for, but cloning is manually done via inlining.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] As using FMV requires code modification on GCC and Clang, vendors more commonly use library multi-versioning: this is easier to achieve as only compiler switches need to be changed.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Glibc supports LMV and this functionality is adopted by the Intel-backed Clear Linux project.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] In 2013 John McCutchan announced that he had created a high-performance interface to SIMD instruction sets for the Dart programming language, bringing the benefits of SIMD to web programs for the first time.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Instances of these types are immutable and in optimized code are mapped directly to SIMD registers.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Operations expressed in Dart typically are compiled into a single instruction without any overhead.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] This is similar to C and C++ intrinsics.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Benchmarks for 4×4 matrix multiplication, 3D vertex transformation, and Mandelbrot set visualization show near 400% speedup compared to scalar code written in Dart.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Intel announced at IDF 2013 that they were implementing McCutchan's specification for both V8 and SpiderMonkey.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] However, by 2017, SIMD.js was taken out of the ECMAScript standard queue in favor of pursuing a similar interface in WebAssembly.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Support for SIMD was added to the WebAssembly 2.0 specification, which was finished on 2022 and became official in December 2024.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] LLVM's autovectoring, when compiling C or C++ to WebAssembly, can target WebAssembly SIMD to automatically make use of SIMD, while SIMD intrinsic are also available.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It has generally proven difficult to find sustainable commercial applications for SIMD-only processors in general-purpose computing.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] One that has had some measure of success is the GAPP, which was developed by Lockheed Martin and taken to the commercial sector by their spin-off Teranex.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] A more ubiquitous application for SIMD is found in video games: nearly every modern video game console since 1998 has incorporated a SIMD processor somewhere in its architecture.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] The PlayStation 2 was unusual in that one of its vector-float units could function as an autonomous digital signal processor (DSP) executing its own instruction stream, or as a coprocessor driven by ordinary CPU instructions.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] 3D graphics applications tend to lend themselves well to SIMD processing as they rely heavily on operations with 4-dimensional vectors.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Microsoft's Direct3D 9.0 now chooses at runtime processor-specific implementations of its own math operations, including the use of SIMD-capable instructions.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] A later processor that used vector processing is the Cell processor used in the PlayStation 3, which was developed by IBM in cooperation with Toshiba and Sony.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It uses a number of SIMD processors (a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture, each with independent local store and controlled by a general purpose CPU) and is geared towards the huge datasets required by 3D and video processing applications.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] It differs from traditional ISAs by being SIMD from the ground up with no separate scalar registers.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Ziilabs produced an SIMD type processor for use on mobile devices, such as media players and mobile phones.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Larger scale commercial SIMD processors are available from ClearSpeed Technology, Ltd. and Stream Processors, Inc.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] ClearSpeed's CSX600 (2004) has 96 cores each with two double-precision floating point units while the CSX700 (2008) has 192.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Stream Processors is headed by computer architect Bill Dally.
[src:cuda-programming/simd] Their Storm-1 processor (2007) contains 80 SIMD cores controlled by a MIPS CPU.
